    <title>Combined summary - Proposal: bip32 version bytes for segwit scripts</title>
    <updated>2023-06-12T18:05:40.350448+00:00</updated>
    <link href="https://lists.linuxfoundation.org/pipermail/bitcoin-dev/2017-September/014916.html" rel="alternate"/>
    <summary>The Bitcoin development community is currently engaged in a debate over the best practices for key management and storage. One proposed solution is to use different version bytes to indicate the type of output script used with public keys, including prefixes such as xprv, xpub, yprv, ypub, zprv, and zpub. This proposal aims to address issues with xpub/xprv serialization by signaling the script type in the version bytes.Wallets must implement all script formats to ensure users can recover their funds from their mnemonic seed. However, the list of script formats keeps growing, making wallet implementation increasingly difficult. Luke Dashjr suggested using the same seed for all script formats, but this view is not shared by everyone.The email thread involves a discussion on expanding the number of version prefixes to eliminate ambiguity regarding P2SH scripts. Kabuto Samourai suggested expanding the number of version prefixes to eliminate ambiguity, but the writer suggests using their "xyz" proposal instead which extends the current format with minimal changes to existing software needed. Removing the p2sh ambiguity would require extra safeguards and handling legacy xpub/xprv differently than ypub and zpub, which would take much longer to deploy.Consensus might be difficult to reach as not all developers will agree on its usefulness. Due to the infinity of possible P2SH scripts, removing ambiguity from a master key associated with a P2SH script would never be possible. Therefore, separating P2SH from P2PKH may not have strong benefits. In conclusion, the Bitcoin development community continues to discuss the best practices for key management and storage. Different version bytes to indicate script types are proposed to address potential issues with xpub/xprv serialization. Wallets must implement all script formats to ensure users can recover their funds, though using a single seed for all formats may lead to seed portability failure. The debate around using the same seed for all formats continues, as it has led to users receiving coins on addresses they do not control.</summary>
